            <p>259 West 45<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Street.<lb/>
                Monday Oct 13&#47;84<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>I am in receipt of yours  of the 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Inst &#38;<lb/> I can assure you that it is only a matter of great<lb/> pleasure to me that I can at any time do any<lb/> thing wherewith I can bestow attention upon<lb/> one who I have such kindly feelings &#38; respect<lb/> as also I can express the same for my wife.<lb/> I procured the book for the perusal of our<lb/> friend after quite a search for it as even the<lb/> Astor Library did not have it &#38; I got it from<lb/> the &#34;Mercantile&#34;¬ù&#44; I took it to him  but he was<lb/> asleep&#44; I left it &#38; since which he has returned<lb/> it after reading it&#45;&#45;&#38; I called this morning<lb/> but again did not see &#94; him as his attendant said<lb/> he was feeling quite poorly <del>this</del> altho for the<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>past two days he had been quite himself&#44; he<lb/> has not gone backwards but continues about<lb/> the same as when you saw him&#44; I shall<lb/>call again in a day or two&#8212;Little did<lb/> I think when we were talking of your Colleague<lb/> Dr Heabich&#91;&#63;&#93; that I should so soon have been<lb/> one of the sad witnesses of the last rites<lb/> to his memory of which duty I have just<lb/> now returned from&#44; I need not tell you of<lb/> the crowded Temple &#38; of the true mourning<lb/> of a congregation &#38; a community who have<lb/> lost a good &#38; conscientious leader &#38; one<lb/> whose void will be hard to fill&#45;&#45;<lb/> the services were unostentatious &#38; impressive.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping this will find you well as also<lb/> your family  &#38; with kind regard&#44; I am yours truly&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>H S&#91;&#63;&#93; Allen<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
